Half the Kingdom by Lore Segal, review
Benjamin Evans enjoys a mischief-making satire on the way we treat the elderly
4
Lore Segal, author of 'Half the Kingdom' Photo: Ellen Dubin	By Benjamin Evans
7:00AM GMT 18 Nov 2013
Comments
In a season in which Donna Tartt and Eleanor Catton have delivered doorstoppers, a slender novel such as Half the Kingdom risks seeming unambitious. Crammed with an unwieldy cast of elderly invalids and peppered with asides to “the reader”, Lore Segal’s latest could hardly seem less fashionable. However, it’s fairly safe to venture that Segal, her literary career spanning half a century, wouldn’t give a hoot. In fact, such is the heedless eccentricity of this dark comedy that it practically loops back towards plausibility again. The story is set in and around a Manhattan hospital as it gets to grips with a baffling epidemic. Every old person who sets foot inside the emergency room, even those just visiting relatives, starts to exhibit sudden-onset Alzheimer’s symptoms. This prompts Joe Bernstine, a terminally ill patient obsessed with the apocalyptic since his retirement from a think tank, to dispatch a posse of undercover researchers on to the wards to find out if his far-fetched theories about terrorism hold any water. Not so much a cohesive narrative as an interconnected series of vignettes, many of Segal’s characters are reeling from the quotidian blows of old age: regret, loneliness, estrangement, miscommunication and declining lucidity. Yet her tonal poise continually offsets the sadness with razor-sharp ironies and gleeful wisecracks. Within its mesh of storylines, perhaps the most deliciously mischievous is that of Lucy Friedgold, a 75-year-old writer whose latest “short-short” has been ignored by her publisher. Tasked with investigating the dementia epidemic by Bernstine, Lucy winds up cornered by orderlies in the hospital café, where she is found brandishing a mobile phone and ceaselessly reciting her “best ever” story to anyone who picks up. Segal’s story technique may be disjointed but the novel hangs together as a satire about how we treat the elderly. Her cast of hospital-bound OAPs, faced with nonsensical bureaucracy and judgmental younger relatives, slip into delusion and despair. Their incident-packed pasts now count for little. It seems many of us prefer to avoid contemplating old age until we suddenly arrive there, but this remarkable novel leads us deftly into the heart of that twilight kingdom. Related Articles
