Dragons' Den teenagers sell 79pc stake in RKA Records
Dragon Duncan Bannatyne backs passion of two Leicester-based 18 year olds and takes a majority stake in their fledgling record label RKA Record's Ryan Ashmore, left, and Liam Webb with Duncan Bannatyne (centre) By Richard Tyler
10:01PM BST 19 Sep 2011
Follow Comments
One of the founders of Dragons’ Den’s RKA Records has said the knowledge they were being offered a life-changing deal meant they willingly accepted Duncan Bannatyne’s demand for a “very, very high stake” in their fledgling venture. Leicester-based Ryan Ashmore and his business partner Liam Webb, both 18, sold 79pc of their business in return for £50,000 in cash and access to the leisure industry entrepreneur’s little black contacts book. Mr Ashmore said the terms of the deal – thought to be the highest amount of equity ever demanded by an investor on the long running BBC TWO show – had initially come as a shock. But as RKA announces its first signing since appearing in the ‘Den’ – Britain’s Got Talent boy band ‘Connected’, who have reformed as ‘Reconnected’ – the pair believe they made the right decision. Ashmore and Webb went into the Den offering only 15pc for £50,000 and prepared to sell 40 to 50pc “at the most.”
Related Articles
Peter Jones sells Wireless Logic to create war chest
15 Aug 2011
Georgette Hewitt: the worst ever Dragons' Den pitch?
02 Aug 2011
How Dragon slayer Kirsty Henshaw survived the Den
15 Jul 2010
“The other four [Dragons] went out pretty quick. At that point we thought never mind, we have tried our best,” said Leicester-based Mr Ashmore. “So it was a bit surprising when he [Bannatyne] said 79pc. We couldn’t try to negotiate because the other four Dragons went out. We said to each other, ‘We have to do this’, although it was for a very, very high stake in the company. I just thought it was so surreal.”
Mr Ashmore, who ran a successful mobile disco from the age of 12, said he thought the pair had won Mr Bannatyne over because of their attitude and potential. “We are so young we think he thought they have to be given a chance. He has seen how driven we are and how determined we are too work,” he said. Mr Ashmore studied music at A-level before leaving his studies after the first year and launching RKA Records said Mr Bannatyne had “opened doors” for RKA at major record labels like EMI, Atlantic and Sony. “With Duncan on board we can walk straight through,” he said. He said having a Dragon as an investor had also helped the PR side of RKA’s sales pitch to potential bands. “It’s played a part. [Connected] are young guys themselves and they have seen what Duncan has seen. We are willing to work 24 hours a day if necessary.”
Mr Ashmore said the £50,000 had been set aside to fund a targeted marketing campaign for Reconnected. “Fifty thousand pounds is not of money if you are going to be stupid with it but we plan to be smart with the money,” he said. He added: “It’s definitely going to be hard. It’s going to get harder before it gets easier. But we are will to give it a go.”
Mr Bannatyne said: “I saw something in Ryan and Liam that caught my imagination. For the past year they have been serving an entrepreneurs’ apprenticeship learning about how to run a business and break into a tough industry. Now, with my investment and hands-on involvement, we can really take the business forward and achieve Ryan and Liam’s ambitions.”
